{"title_page": "Gurjars of Kutch", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{expert needed|date=August 2010}}\n{{infobox ethnic group|\n| group            = Gurjar<br /> Mistri <br />Mestri\n| population       = 51,000{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n| popplace         = India\n| langs            = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n| rels             = Hindu\n| related          = [[Mistri (caste)|Mistri]], [[Gurjar Kshatriya Kadia]], [[Salaat (caste)|Salaat]], [[Chunara]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\nThe [[Gurjar|Gurjars]] of [[Kutch]]<ref name=e>{{cite news|title=\u0aae\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab0\u0abe\u0ab7\u0acd\u0a9f\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aa8\u0abe \u0aa8\u0abe\u0a97\u0aaa\u0ac1\u0ab0 \u0a96\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0a9a\u0acd\u0a9b \u0a97\u0ac1\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9c\u0ab0 \u0a95\u0acd\u0ab7\u0aa4\u0acd\u0ab0\u0abf\u0aaf \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c \u0ab0\u0abe\u0ab7\u0acd\u0a9f\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aaf \u0aae\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab8\u0aad\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0a85\u0aa7\u0abf\u0ab5\u0ac7\u0ab6\u0aa8 (Election of President of Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj held at Nagpur, Maharashtra)|url=http://www.gujaratsamachar.com/20110607/gujarat/kutch4.html|accessdate=20 July 2012|newspaper=Gujarat Samachar|date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516162804/http://gujaratsamachar.com/20110607/gujarat/kutch4.html|archivedate=16 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=db>{{cite news|title=\u0ab8\u0aae\u0ac2\u0ab9 \u0ab2\u0a97\u0acd\u0aa8\u0acb\u0aa5\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c \u0a97\u0abf\u0aa0\u0aa4 \u0aa5\u0abe\u0aaf / 38th Mass community marriage Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya held at Anjar|url=http://www.divyabhaskar.co.in/article/KUT-1188171-1833300.html|accessdate=31 July 2012|newspaper=Divya Bhaskar|date=9 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=HC raps mgmt of Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj-Gondia|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-24/nagpur/29698752_1_writ-petition-court-receiver-appeal|accessdate=20 July 2012|newspaper=Times of India|date=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=db1>{{cite news|title=\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u0920 \u0939\u0948 \u0915\u091a\u094d\u091b \u0917\u0941\u0930\u094d\u091c\u0930 \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0938\u092e\u093e\u091c (Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj people are hardworking)|url=http://www.bhaskar.com/article/CHH-OTH-1645943-2618166.html|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=Dainik Bhaskar|date=6 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011142039/http://www.bhaskar.com/article/CHH-OTH-1645943-2618166.html|archivedate=11 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0938\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0947\u0932\u0928 \u0928\u0947 \u0916\u0924\u094d\u092e \u0915\u0940 \u091d\u093f\u091d\u0915, \u0905\u092c \u092c\u0938\u094d\u0924\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092d\u0940 \u092c\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0939 \u0915\u0930\u0915\u0947 \u0906\u090f\u0902\u0917\u0940 \u0917\u0941\u091c\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0940 \u092c\u0947\u091f\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0902 (\u0915\u091a\u094d\u091b \u0917\u0941\u0930\u094d\u091c\u0930 \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0917\u0941\u091c\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0940 \u0938\u092e\u093e\u091c \u0915\u093e \u0905\u0916\u093f\u0932 \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940\u092f \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0938\u092d\u093e ) |url=https://www.bhaskar.com/chhatisgarh/raipur/news/latest-jagdalpur-news-024002-1861843.html |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=Dainik Bhaskar |date=3 June 2018 |language=hi}}</ref> (also known as '''Mistri'''<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0aae\u0a82\u0aa6\u0abf\u0ab0 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0a95\u0ab0\u0aa3\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a96\u0acb\u0a9f\u0abe \u0a95\u0ac7\u0ab8 \u0aa5\u0abe\u0aaf \u0aa4\u0ac7\u0ab5\u0acb \u0aae\u0abf\u0ab8\u0acd\u0aa4\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aad\u0aaf  Barla Mandir case - Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya / Mistri Samaj of Madhapar afraid of false implication|url=https://www.divyabhaskar.co.in/news/100206041820_mandir_case.html|accessdate=27 April 2019|newspaper=Divya Bhaskar|date=6 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=Shambles/> or '''Mestri'''<ref name=ks/><ref name=gj1>{{cite book|title=Gujarat, Part 1  By Kumar Suresh Singh, Rajendra Behari Lal|year=2003|pages=912\u2013915|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Cy_-FXW9BQC&pg=PA912&lpg=PA912&dq=Mestri+KUTCH&source=bl&ots=WxwNSfG5TZ&sig=DxjU9-T8UY_tXhouYHybuxuYm4U&hl=en&sa=X&ei=E6paUP_HKY3rrQeImICQDw&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Mestri%20KUTCH&f=false}}</ref>) are a minority [[Hindu]] and one of the [[Socially and Educationally Backward Class|Socially and Educationally Backward]] communities of [[Gujarat]]<ref name=gjs>[http://sje.gujarat.gov.in/ddcw/showpage.aspx?contentid=1736&lang=english List of Socially and Educationally Backward Classes declared by Gujarat State]</ref> in India, who claim to be [[Kshatriya]]s.<ref name=gj1/>  They are an artisan community related with [[Kadia (term)|Kadia]] works. They are also known as the [[Mistri (caste)|Mistri]] or '''Mistris of Kutch'''.<ref name=Shambles/><ref name=ks>{{cite book|title=India's communities by Kumar Suresh Singh|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=2287|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=FLNSUKOPBIfzrQeTk4CYDA&id=1lZuAAAAMAAJ&dq=MISTRI+COMMUNITY+KUTCH&q=MISTRI++KUTCH#search_anchor|quote=MESTRI: They are also known as Mistri. Kota in Rajasthan is believed to be their native place from where they came to Kutch in vs 1234 in search of livelihood. In Gujarat, the community is distributed in about eighteen villages of the Bhuj and Anjar}}</ref><ref name=M>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzbkTbqgGEoC&pg=PA316&lpg=PA316&dq=kadia+kumbhar+kshatriyas&source=bl&ots=hLQKmbP9N4&sig=VEM_blcLOCV6wks9KAWr7SsUPTE&hl=en&ei=VBnJTIXoIoKucPOpmcgO&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=mistri&f=false Mistri] Encyclopaedia of Backward Castes By Neelam Yadav Page 316.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzbkTbqgGEoC&pg=PA316&lpg=PA316&dq=kadia+kumbhar+kshatriyas&source=bl&ots=hLQKmbP9N4&sig=VEM_blcLOCV6wks9KAWr7SsUPTE&hl=en&ei=VBnJTIXoIoKucPOpmcgO&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAjgK#v=snippet&q=kadia&f=false Kadia, Gurjar Ksahtriya Kadia, Gurjar Kadia] Encyclopaedia of Backward Castes By Neelam Yadav Page 264, 316</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Paliyas belonging to Mistris of Kutch at Dhaneti.jpg|thumb|''[[Paliya]]''s belonging to war heroes of Mistris of Kutch, standing at [[Dhaneti]] dating back to 1178 AD]]\n\nThe community is believed to be from [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]]<ref name=ks/> and first entered into [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] and founded 36 villages in the area, while others moved further into Kutch. Around 1177\u201378 AD ([[Vikram Samvant|VS]] 1234), a major group migrated to Kutch from Saurashtra<ref name=ks/> under the leadership of Patel Ganga Maru.<ref name=kgk/> They settled in the village of [[Dhaneti]].<ref name=D>Kumar Ganti Itihass (History of Kumar Gnati) Published in year 1896.</ref><ref name=kgk/> There are several [[Paliya|Paria]]s of the community, located near village pond of Dhaneti, standing as memorials of the war that was fought in 1178 AD. The community members still go once every year to offer [[Puja (Hinduism)|pooja]] and their respects to their fore-fathers.<ref name=dh>{{cite news|title=\u0aa7\u0abe\u0aa3\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ac0 \u0a96\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0a9a\u0acd\u0a9b \u0a97\u0ac1.\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab7. \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c...(Pooja held at Dhaneti by Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya for their Shurapura & Dada)|url=http://www.kutchmitradaily.com/article.aspx?site_id=3&news_id=17476|accessdate=9 July 2013|newspaper=Kutch Mitra Daily|date=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis group, later, made their distinct identity not only by building historical forts, palaces, temples and architects not only in Kutch but also all over British India, primarily in the fields of railways and coal mining.<ref name=Shambles>{{cite web|url=http://www.expressindia.com/news/ie/daily/20010312/ina12017.html |title=In the shambles of Pride of Kutch lies priceless art |publisher=Expressindia.com |date=2001-03-12 |accessdate=2013-09-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121220074425/http://www.expressindia.com/news/ie/daily/20010312/ina12017.html |archivedate=20 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas left Dhaneti and went on to establish eighteen villages in Kutch<ref name=ks/> which were granted to them by the King: [[Anjar, India|Anjar]], [[Sinugra]], [[Khambhra]], [[Nagalpar]], [[Khedoi]], [[Madhapar]], [[Hajapar]], [[Kukma]], [[Galpadar]], [[Reha]], [[Vidi]], [[Jambudi]], [[Devaliya]], [[Lovaria]], [[Nagor]], [[Meghpar(Anjar)|Meghpar]], [[Chandiya]] and [[Kumbharia, Kutch District, Gujarat|Kumbharia]].<ref name=kgk/>\n\nOver the centuries, they have been known or identified by some other names like [[Kadia (term)|Kadia]]s, [[Kadia Kshatriyas]] and Kumar Gnati.<ref name=M/><ref name=kgk/>\n\n==Culture==\nThey are a Hindu community. Some are followers of [[Swaminarayan]] and [[Pranami]] sect of Hinduism, They are vegetarian in diet and avoid consumption of alcohol. The staple food is [[khichdi]], vegetables, pulses and [[Butter milk|butter-milk]].<ref name=gj1/>\n\nThe community consists of clans like [[Rathod]], [[Chauhan]], [[Yadav]], [[Chawda]], [[Jethwa]], [[Padhiar]], [[Yadav]], [[Chudasama]], [[Parmar]], [[Taunk]], Khodiyar, [[Solanki (clan)|Solanki]], [[Sarvaiya|Sawaria]], Vaghela, Vegad, Varu, [[Maru (surname)|Maru]], [[Bhalsod]], etc., who enjoy same status. However, most of people prefer to pre-fix Mistri to their name.<ref name=gj1/>\n\nThe community  are an [[endogamy|endogamous]] community who practice the principle of clan [[exogamy]]. [[Dowry]] is generally not asked for, neither practice of [[bride price]] is there in community. Divorce is generally not encouraged; however, divorce can be claimed in certain cases.<ref name=gj1/>\n\nBetrothal ceremony generally precedes marriage, which is held usually within one year of engagement and marriage is observed as per Hindu rites by [[Saptapadi|taking seven circumambulation of fire]].<ref name=gj1/>\n\nWidow remarriage (''ghargenu'') is allowed, where the women is usually married outside husband's family.<ref name=kgk/><ref name=gj1/>\n\n==In Kutch==\n[[File:Chabutro Sinugra.jpg|thumb|A [[Chabutro]] built by Seth Khora Ramji Chawda in year 1900 standing at village Sinugra, shows the unique architect and skill of Mistris of Kutch.]]\nThe Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas were master craftsmen, architects and contractors and have played a major role in erection and construction of the majority of forts, palaces and architecture of Kutch. It was because of this they came to be known as Mistri in Kutch.<ref name=ks/>\n\n==Indian railways==\n{{main|Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas contributions to the Indian railways}}\n\nIt was during 1850 to 1930 AD that the KGK migrated outside Kutch and were involved in the construction of major rail-bridges and the laying down of railway tracks in almost all major rail routes of undivided British India doing the \"Railway Thekedari\" ([[Railway]] [[Contractors]] also ''Thikadari'') and as [[Contractors|Thekedar]] (or Thikadar) in [[Irrigation]] projects and Forest Department and Public Works Department.<ref name=kgk/> They have also done major roadway, road bridges, canal works, irrigation dams and barrage work throughout [[British India]] from 1850 to 1980. The communities largest contribution is in the building of the early railway lines and bridges throughout British India. Their works in Railway construction span from 1850 to 1980 for more than one and a quarter of century.\n\n==Docks, dams and canals in British India==\n\nThe KGK contributed to the building of docks, dams, barrages and irrigation canals between 1850 and 1980,{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} and they in the eighteenth century had been among the communities who built the first [[Bombay Port Trust|ports of Bombay]] and [[Hornby Vellard]]. Other docks were developed in Bombay during 1870\u20131895 (Prince's Docks built in 1885 and Victoria Docks built in 1891<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Gatten, TNN 13 December 2008, 04.29am IST |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-12-13/mumbai/27945763_1_victoria-docks-port-cities-harbour |title=Prince's and Victoria docks in state of decay |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref>) in which many Mistris of Kutch and Kadia Kshatriyas of Saurashtra worked. The Mandavi Docks, bridge over Rukhmavati at [[Mandavi]] and many road bridges across territories of British India are built by the community using their mason's skills.<ref name=kgk/>\n\n==Mining==\n\nIn the regions of British India known as [[Bengal]], [[Bihar]] and [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], the Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas pioneered Indian involvement in coal mining from 1894. They broke the previous monopolies held by British and other Europeans, establishing many collieries at l Jharia coalfields and Ranigunj coalfield.<ref name=Y>''Diary of Golden Days at Jharia&nbsp;\u2013 A Memoir and History of Gurjar Kashtriya community of Kutch in Coalfields of Jharia''&nbsp;\u2013 written by Natwarlal Devram Jethwa of Calcutta (1998).</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=U-P9Us_wFsHIrQeb7oCIDw&id=rbNHAAAAYAAJ&dq=gujarati+dhanbad+coal+railway&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=expert+contractor|title=Census of India, 1981: Bihar. Series 4|last=|first=|publisher=Controller of Publications - Bihar|year=1981|isbn=|location=|page=22|pages=|quote=It was the existence of coal that first attracted the railway authority to extend the railways and with them came the Gujarati people as an expert railway contractor with an experience of railway construction work at Thana. They then met Raja of Jharia and purchased some having underneath wast wealth in shape of coal.}}</ref>\n\n[[Seth Khora Ramji]] of Sinugra was the first Indian to break the British monopoly in the Jharia Coalfields.<ref name=Y/><ref name=K>Encyclopedia of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa by British Authority (1920)</ref> Natwarlal Devram Jethwa<ref name=Y/> says that {{quote|The East Indian Railway in 1894-95 extended its line from [[Barakar]] to [[Dhanbad]] via [[Katras]] and [[Jharia]]. Messrs. Khora Ramji in 1894 was working on railway lines contract of Jharia branch line and with his brother Jetha Lira was also building Jharia Railway Station, when he discovered coal in Jharia belt. The location of his three collieries named [[Jeenagora]], Khas Jherria, Gareria is mentioned also in 1917 Gazetteers of Bengal, Assam, Bihar and Orissa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/bengalassambehar00playuoft/bengalassambehar00playuoft_djvu.txt |title=Gazetteers of Bengal, Assam, Bihar and Orissa 1917 Khora Ramji Colliries |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref>}}\n\n==Downturn in fortunes==\nThe majority of the once-prosperous KGK community living in Kutch and Saurashtra today are devoid of agricultural land due to land reform acts post independence of India. Presently Mistri are in the list of Socially and Educationally Backward Class community in Gujarat, however, those who are not domicile of Gujarat state cannot take advantage of this reservation.<ref name=gjs/><ref name=M/>\n\n==Present status==\n\n===Distribution in India===\nKGK community members are found throughout India and Communities associations exist in the states of Gujarat, Maharashtra, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh, Telengana, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Rajasthan, Delhi, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, Bihar, Orissa and West Bengal.<ref name=kgk/>\n\n===Present day identity===\nThe community on national level is referred as \"Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya\" mostly in present-day India. However, the \"Mistri\", which was mostly used during the last century and before is nowadays only used in Kutch and Gujarat. The term Mestri to refer to community is recognized by Government of Gujarat and  the [[Other Backward Class]] Certificate as per the ''Bakshi Panch'' report.<ref name=gjs/><ref name=M/><ref name=kgk>''Kutch Gurjar Kshatriys : A brief History & Glory: by Raja Pawan Jethwa. (2007) Calcutta.'' <!--Turn into a note--> The Book has separate sections: INTRODUCTION : Gives an overview of Kutch Gurjar Kshtriya community and its ancient history (I) KGK and Architect built by them mainly in Princely State of Cutch. (II) KGK and Railway : Gives details of some major Railway work with mileage wise details (III) KGK Surnames & History : Section gives details of various Kshatriya clan's history and origin of their surnames. (IV) Section deals with Kuldevi names various clans of KGK worship.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Tribes of Kutch]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Kutch district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{expert needed|date=August 2010}}\n{{infobox ethnic group|\n|group= Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya<br /> Mistri <br />Mestri\n|population = 51,000{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n|popplace = India\n|langs = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n|rels= Hindu \n|related= [[Mistri (caste)|Mistri]], [[Gurjar Kshatriya Kadia]], [[Salaat (caste)|Salaat]], [[Chunara]]\n}}\n\n'''Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya'''<ref name=e>{{cite news|title=\u0aae\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab0\u0abe\u0ab7\u0acd\u0a9f\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aa8\u0abe \u0aa8\u0abe\u0a97\u0aaa\u0ac1\u0ab0 \u0a96\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0a9a\u0acd\u0a9b \u0a97\u0ac1\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9c\u0ab0 \u0a95\u0acd\u0ab7\u0aa4\u0acd\u0ab0\u0abf\u0aaf \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c \u0ab0\u0abe\u0ab7\u0acd\u0a9f\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aaf \u0aae\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab8\u0aad\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0a85\u0aa7\u0abf\u0ab5\u0ac7\u0ab6\u0aa8 (Election of President of Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj held at Nagpur, Maharashtra)|url=http://www.gujaratsamachar.com/20110607/gujarat/kutch4.html|accessdate=20 July 2012|newspaper=Gujarat Samachar|date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516162804/http://gujaratsamachar.com/20110607/gujarat/kutch4.html|archivedate=16 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=db>{{cite news|title=\u0ab8\u0aae\u0ac2\u0ab9 \u0ab2\u0a97\u0acd\u0aa8\u0acb\u0aa5\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c \u0a97\u0abf\u0aa0\u0aa4 \u0aa5\u0abe\u0aaf / 38th Mass community marriage Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya held at Anjar|url=http://www.divyabhaskar.co.in/article/KUT-1188171-1833300.html|accessdate=31 July 2012|newspaper=Divya Bhaskar|date=9 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=HC raps mgmt of Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj-Gondia|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-24/nagpur/29698752_1_writ-petition-court-receiver-appeal|accessdate=20 July 2012|newspaper=Times of India|date=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=db1>{{cite news|title=\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u0920 \u0939\u0948 \u0915\u091a\u094d\u091b \u0917\u0941\u0930\u094d\u091c\u0930 \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0938\u092e\u093e\u091c (Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj people are hardworking)|url=http://www.bhaskar.com/article/CHH-OTH-1645943-2618166.html|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=Dainik Bhaskar|date=6 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011142039/http://www.bhaskar.com/article/CHH-OTH-1645943-2618166.html|archivedate=11 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0938\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0947\u0932\u0928 \u0928\u0947 \u0916\u0924\u094d\u092e \u0915\u0940 \u091d\u093f\u091d\u0915, \u0905\u092c \u092c\u0938\u094d\u0924\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092d\u0940 \u092c\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0939 \u0915\u0930\u0915\u0947 \u0906\u090f\u0902\u0917\u0940 \u0917\u0941\u091c\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0940 \u092c\u0947\u091f\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0902 (\u0915\u091a\u094d\u091b \u0917\u0941\u0930\u094d\u091c\u0930 \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0917\u0941\u091c\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0940 \u0938\u092e\u093e\u091c \u0915\u093e \u0905\u0916\u093f\u0932 \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940\u092f \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0938\u092d\u093e ) |url=https://www.bhaskar.com/chhatisgarh/raipur/news/latest-jagdalpur-news-024002-1861843.html |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=Dainik Bhaskar |date=3 June 2018 |language=hi}}</ref> (also known as '''Mistri'''<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0aae\u0a82\u0aa6\u0abf\u0ab0 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0a95\u0ab0\u0aa3\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a96\u0acb\u0a9f\u0abe \u0a95\u0ac7\u0ab8 \u0aa5\u0abe\u0aaf \u0aa4\u0ac7\u0ab5\u0acb \u0aae\u0abf\u0ab8\u0acd\u0aa4\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aad\u0aaf  Barla Mandir case - Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya / Mistri Samaj of Madhapar afraid of false implication|url=https://www.divyabhaskar.co.in/news/100206041820_mandir_case.html|accessdate=27 April 2019|newspaper=Divya Bhaskar|date=6 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=Shambles/> or '''Mestri'''<ref name=ks/><ref name=gj1>{{cite book|title=Gujarat, Part 1  By Kumar Suresh Singh, Rajendra Behari Lal|year=2003|pages=912\u2013915|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Cy_-FXW9BQC&pg=PA912&lpg=PA912&dq=Mestri+KUTCH&source=bl&ots=WxwNSfG5TZ&sig=DxjU9-T8UY_tXhouYHybuxuYm4U&hl=en&sa=X&ei=E6paUP_HKY3rrQeImICQDw&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Mestri%20KUTCH&f=false}}</ref>) are a minority [[Hindu]] and one of the [[Socially and Educationally Backward Class|Socially and Educationally Backward]] communities of [[Gujarat]]<ref name=gjs>[http://sje.gujarat.gov.in/ddcw/showpage.aspx?contentid=1736&lang=english List of Socially and Educationally Backward Classes declared by Gujarat State]</ref> in India, who claim to be [[Kshatriya]]s.<ref name=gj1/>  They are an artisan community related with [[Kadia (term)|Kadia]] works. They are also known as the [[Mistri (caste)|Mistri]] or '''Mistris of Kutch'''.<ref name=Shambles/><ref name=ks>{{cite book|title=India's communities by Kumar Suresh Singh|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=2287|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=FLNSUKOPBIfzrQeTk4CYDA&id=1lZuAAAAMAAJ&dq=MISTRI+COMMUNITY+KUTCH&q=MISTRI++KUTCH#search_anchor|quote=MESTRI: They are also known as Mistri. Kota in Rajasthan is believed to be their native place from where they came to Kutch in vs 1234 in search of livelihood. In Gujarat, the community is distributed in about eighteen villages of the Bhuj and Anjar}}</ref><ref name=M>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzbkTbqgGEoC&pg=PA316&lpg=PA316&dq=kadia+kumbhar+kshatriyas&source=bl&ots=hLQKmbP9N4&sig=VEM_blcLOCV6wks9KAWr7SsUPTE&hl=en&ei=VBnJTIXoIoKucPOpmcgO&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=mistri&f=false Mistri] Encyclopaedia of Backward Castes By Neelam Yadav Page 316.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzbkTbqgGEoC&pg=PA316&lpg=PA316&dq=kadia+kumbhar+kshatriyas&source=bl&ots=hLQKmbP9N4&sig=VEM_blcLOCV6wks9KAWr7SsUPTE&hl=en&ei=VBnJTIXoIoKucPOpmcgO&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAjgK#v=snippet&q=kadia&f=false Kadia, Gurjar Ksahtriya Kadia, Gurjar Kadia] Encyclopaedia of Backward Castes By Neelam Yadav Page 264, 316</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Paliyas belonging to Mistris of Kutch at Dhaneti.jpg|thumb|''[[Paliya]]''s belonging to war heroes of Mistris of Kutch, standing at [[Dhaneti]] dating back to 1178 AD]]\n\nThe community is believed to be from [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]]<ref name=ks/> and first entered into [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] and founded 36 villages in the area, while others moved further into Kutch. Around 1177\u201378 AD ([[Vikram Samvant|VS]] 1234), a major group migrated to Kutch from Saurashtra<ref name=ks/> under the leadership of Patel Ganga Maru.<ref name=kgk/> They settled in the village of [[Dhaneti]].<ref name=D>Kumar Ganti Itihass (History of Kumar Gnati) Published in year 1896.</ref><ref name=kgk/> There are several [[Paliya|Paria]]s of the community, located near village pond of Dhaneti, standing as memorials of the war that was fought in 1178 AD. The community members still go once every year to offer [[Puja (Hinduism)|pooja]] and their respects to their fore-fathers.<ref name=dh>{{cite news|title=\u0aa7\u0abe\u0aa3\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ac0 \u0a96\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0a9a\u0acd\u0a9b \u0a97\u0ac1.\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab7. \u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a9c...(Pooja held at Dhaneti by Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya for their Shurapura & Dada)|url=http://www.kutchmitradaily.com/article.aspx?site_id=3&news_id=17476|accessdate=9 July 2013|newspaper=Kutch Mitra Daily|date=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis group, later, made their distinct identity not only by building historical forts, palaces, temples and architects not only in Kutch but also all over British India, primarily in the fields of railways and coal mining.<ref name=Shambles>{{cite web|url=http://www.expressindia.com/news/ie/daily/20010312/ina12017.html |title=In the shambles of Pride of Kutch lies priceless art |publisher=Expressindia.com |date=2001-03-12 |accessdate=2013-09-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121220074425/http://www.expressindia.com/news/ie/daily/20010312/ina12017.html |archivedate=20 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas left Dhaneti and went on to establish eighteen villages in Kutch<ref name=ks/> which were granted to them by the King: [[Anjar, India|Anjar]], [[Sinugra]], [[Khambhra]], [[Nagalpar]], [[Khedoi]], [[Madhapar]], [[Hajapar]], [[Kukma]], [[Galpadar]], [[Reha]], [[Vidi]], [[Jambudi]], [[Devaliya]], [[Lovaria]], [[Nagor]], [[Meghpar(Anjar)|Meghpar]], [[Chandiya]] and [[Kumbharia, Kutch District, Gujarat|Kumbharia]].<ref name=kgk/>\n\nOver the centuries, they have been known or identified by some other names like [[Kadia (term)|Kadia]]s, [[Kadia Kshatriyas]] and Kumar Gnati.<ref name=M/><ref name=kgk/>\n\n==Culture==\nThey are a Hindu community. Some are followers of [[Swaminarayan]] and [[Pranami]] sect of Hinduism, They are vegetarian in diet and avoid consumption of alcohol. The staple food is [[khichdi]], vegetables, pulses and [[Butter milk|butter-milk]].<ref name=gj1/>\n\nThe community consists of clans like [[Rathod]], [[Chauhan]], [[Yadav]], [[Chawda]], [[Jethwa]], [[Padhiar]], [[Yadav]], [[Chudasama]], [[Parmar]], [[Taunk]], Khodiyar, [[Solanki (clan)|Solanki]], [[Sarvaiya|Sawaria]], Vaghela, Vegad, Varu, [[Maru (surname)|Maru]], [[Bhalsod]], etc., who enjoy same status. However, most of people prefer to pre-fix Mistri to their name.<ref name=gj1/>\n\nThe community  are an [[endogamy|endogamous]] community who practice the principle of clan [[exogamy]]. [[Dowry]] is generally not asked for, neither practice of [[bride price]] is there in community. Divorce is generally not encouraged; however, divorce can be claimed in certain cases.<ref name=gj1/>\n\nBetrothal ceremony generally precedes marriage, which is held usually within one year of engagement and marriage is observed as per Hindu rites by [[Saptapadi|taking seven circumambulation of fire]].<ref name=gj1/>\n\nWidow remarriage (''ghargenu'') is allowed, where the women is usually married outside husband's family.<ref name=kgk/><ref name=gj1/>\n\n==In Kutch==\n[[File:Chabutro Sinugra.jpg|thumb|A [[Chabutro]] built by Seth Khora Ramji Chawda in year 1900 standing at village Sinugra, shows the unique architect and skill of Mistris of Kutch.]]\nThe Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas were master craftsmen, architects and contractors and have played a major role in erection and construction of the majority of forts, palaces and architecture of Kutch. It was because of this they came to be known as Mistri in Kutch.<ref name=ks/>\n\n==Indian railways==\n{{main|Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas contributions to the Indian railways}}\n\nIt was during 1850 to 1930 AD that the KGK migrated outside Kutch and were involved in the construction of major rail-bridges and the laying down of railway tracks in almost all major rail routes of undivided British India doing the \"Railway Thekedari\" ([[Railway]] [[Contractors]] also ''Thikadari'') and as [[Contractors|Thekedar]] (or Thikadar) in [[Irrigation]] projects and Forest Department and Public Works Department.<ref name=kgk/> They have also done major roadway, road bridges, canal works, irrigation dams and barrage work throughout [[British India]] from 1850 to 1980. The communities largest contribution is in the building of the early railway lines and bridges throughout British India. Their works in Railway construction span from 1850 to 1980 for more than one and a quarter of century.\n\n==Docks, dams and canals in British India==\n\nThe KGK contributed to the building of docks, dams, barrages and irrigation canals between 1850 and 1980,{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} and they in the eighteenth century had been among the communities who built the first [[Bombay Port Trust|ports of Bombay]] and [[Hornby Vellard]]. Other docks were developed in Bombay during 1870\u20131895 (Prince's Docks built in 1885 and Victoria Docks built in 1891<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Gatten, TNN 13 December 2008, 04.29am IST |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-12-13/mumbai/27945763_1_victoria-docks-port-cities-harbour |title=Prince's and Victoria docks in state of decay |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref>) in which many Mistris of Kutch and Kadia Kshatriyas of Saurashtra worked. The Mandavi Docks, bridge over Rukhmavati at [[Mandavi]] and many road bridges across territories of British India are built by the community using their mason's skills.<ref name=kgk/>\n\n==Mining==\n\nIn the regions of British India known as [[Bengal]], [[Bihar]] and [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], the Kutch Gurjar Kshatriyas pioneered Indian involvement in coal mining from 1894. They broke the previous monopolies held by British and other Europeans, establishing many collieries at l Jharia coalfields and Ranigunj coalfield.<ref name=Y>''Diary of Golden Days at Jharia&nbsp;\u2013 A Memoir and History of Gurjar Kashtriya community of Kutch in Coalfields of Jharia''&nbsp;\u2013 written by Natwarlal Devram Jethwa of Calcutta (1998).</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=U-P9Us_wFsHIrQeb7oCIDw&id=rbNHAAAAYAAJ&dq=gujarati+dhanbad+coal+railway&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=expert+contractor|title=Census of India, 1981: Bihar. Series 4|last=|first=|publisher=Controller of Publications - Bihar|year=1981|isbn=|location=|page=22|pages=|quote=It was the existence of coal that first attracted the railway authority to extend the railways and with them came the Gujarati people as an expert railway contractor with an experience of railway construction work at Thana. They then met Raja of Jharia and purchased some having underneath wast wealth in shape of coal.}}</ref>\n\n[[Seth Khora Ramji]] of Sinugra was the first Indian to break the British monopoly in the Jharia Coalfields.<ref name=Y/><ref name=K>Encyclopedia of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa by British Authority (1920)</ref> Natwarlal Devram Jethwa<ref name=Y/> says that {{quote|The East Indian Railway in 1894-95 extended its line from [[Barakar]] to [[Dhanbad]] via [[Katras]] and [[Jharia]]. Messrs. Khora Ramji in 1894 was working on railway lines contract of Jharia branch line and with his brother Jetha Lira was also building Jharia Railway Station, when he discovered coal in Jharia belt. The location of his three collieries named [[Jeenagora]], Khas Jherria, Gareria is mentioned also in 1917 Gazetteers of Bengal, Assam, Bihar and Orissa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/bengalassambehar00playuoft/bengalassambehar00playuoft_djvu.txt |title=Gazetteers of Bengal, Assam, Bihar and Orissa 1917 Khora Ramji Colliries |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref>}}\n\n==Downturn in fortunes==\nThe majority of the once-prosperous KGK community living in Kutch and Saurashtra today are devoid of agricultural land due to land reform acts post independence of India. Presently Mistri are in the list of Socially and Educationally Backward Class community in Gujarat, however, those who are not domicile of Gujarat state cannot take advantage of this reservation.<ref name=gjs/><ref name=M/>\n\n==Present status==\n\n===Distribution in India===\nKGK community members are found throughout India and Communities associations exist in the states of Gujarat, Maharashtra, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh, Telengana, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Rajasthan, Delhi, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, Bihar, Orissa and West Bengal.<ref name=kgk/>\n\n===Present day identity===\nThe community on national level is referred as \"Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya\" mostly in present-day India. However, the \"Mistri\", which was mostly used during the last century and before is nowadays only used in Kutch and Gujarat. The term Mestri to refer to community is recognized by Government of Gujarat and  the [[Other Backward Class]] Certificate as per the ''Bakshi Panch'' report.<ref name=gjs/><ref name=M/><ref name=kgk>''Kutch Gurjar Kshatriys : A brief History & Glory: by Raja Pawan Jethwa. (2007) Calcutta.'' <!--Turn into a note--> The Book has separate sections: INTRODUCTION : Gives an overview of Kutch Gurjar Kshtriya community and its ancient history (I) KGK and Architect built by them mainly in Princely State of Cutch. (II) KGK and Railway : Gives details of some major Railway work with mileage wise details (III) KGK Surnames & History : Section gives details of various Kshatriya clan's history and origin of their surnames. (IV) Section deals with Kuldevi names various clans of KGK worship.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Tribes of Kutch]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Kutch district]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Improvement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurjars_of_Kutch"}
{"title_page": "Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial", "text_new": "'''Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial''' (20 March 1947 \u2013 6 September 2012) was an Argentinian-born writer and translator who lived in Spain from 1968, mostly in [[Barcelona]].<ref name=lah>{{cite web |url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=570840&CategoryId=13003 |title=Spain\u2019s Great Forgotten Writer Horacio Vazquez-Rial Dies |work=Latin American Herald Tribune |date=September 7, 2012 |accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Clarin\">{{cite news|url=http://www.revistaenie.clarin.com/literatura/murio-Horacio-Vazquez-Rial_0_769123291.html|title=Muri\u00f3 en Madrid el escritor argentino Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial|date=12-9-6|publisher=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 September 2012}}</ref> He was nominated for the [[Nadal Prize]] in 1987 for ''Historia del triste'', and in March 1989 he was a finalist for the fifth edition of the [[Plaza y Janes Prize]] for ''La Reina de oros''.<ref name=lah/> His only work available in English is ''Triste's History''.   He died in [[Madrid]], aged 65.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vazquezrial.com/ Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial], official website\n*{{worldcat id|lccn-n86-51360}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vazquez-Rial, Horacio}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Argentine male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Argentine descent]]\n[[Category:People from Barcelona]]\n", "text_old": "'''Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial''' (20 March 1947 \u2013 6 September 2012) was an Argentinian-born writer and translator who lived in Spain from 1968, mostly in [[Barcelona]].<ref name=lah>{{cite web |url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=570840&CategoryId=13003 |title=Spain\u2019s Great Forgotten Writer Horacio Vazquez-Rial Dies |work=Latin American Herald Tribune |date=September 7, 2012 |accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Clarin\">{{cite news|url=http://www.revistaenie.clarin.com/literatura/murio-Horacio-Vazquez-Rial_0_769123291.html|title=Muri\u00f3 en Madrid el escritor argentino Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial|date=12-9-6|publisher=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 September 2012}}</ref> He was nominated for the [[Nadal Prize]] in 1987 for ''Historia del triste'', and in March 1989 he was a finalist for the fifth edition of the [[Plaza y Janes Prize]] for ''La Reina de oros''.<ref name=lah/> His only work available in English is ''Triste's History''.   He died in [[Madrid]], aged 65.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vazquezrial.com/ Horacio V\u00e1zquez-Rial], official website\n*{{worldcat id|lccn-n86-51360}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vazquez-Rial, Horacio}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Argentine male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Argentine descent]]\n[[Category:People from Barcelona]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horacio_V%C3%A1zquez-Rial"}
{"title_page": "BMW 2 Series (F44)", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = BMW 2 Series Gran Coup\u00e9 (F44)\n| image        = 2020 BMW 2-Series 218i Gran Coup\u00e9 M Sport.jpg\n| caption      = 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe F44\n| manufacturer = [[BMW]]\n| aka          = \n| production   = November 2019\u2013present\n| assembly     = Germany: [[Leipzig]] ([[BMW Central Building|BMW Group Plant Leipzig]])\n| class        = [[Compact executive car|Subcompact executive car]]\n| body_style   = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| layout       = {{ubl\n  | [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel drive]]\n  | [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, all-wheel drive]] ([[xDrive]])\n  }}\n| platform     = [[BMW UKL platform]]\n| related      = [[BMW 1 Series (F40)]]\n| engine       = {{ubl\n  | 1.5 L [[BMW B38|''B38'']] [[straight-three engine|I3]]-[[turbocharger|T]] (petrol)\n  | 2.0 L [[BMW B47|''B47'']] [[inline-four engine|I4]]-[[turbocharger|T]] (diesel)\n  | 2.0 L [[BMW B48|''B46'' / ''B48'']] [[inline-four engine|I4]]-[[turbocharger|T]] (petrol)\n  }}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n  | 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n  | 8-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  | 7-speed [[dual-clutch transmission|DCT]]\n  }}\n| propulsion   = \n| wheelbase    = {{convert|2670|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|4526|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width        = {{convert|1800|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height       = {{convert|1420|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight       = {{convert|1350|-|1570|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| sp           = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''F44 BMW 2 Series''' is a [[subcompact car|subcompact executive car]] produced by [[BMW]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmwblog.com/2019/10/15/world-premiere-the-first-ever-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe/|title=WORLD PREMIERE: The first Ever BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|date=2019-10-15|website=BMW BLOG|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> It is also known as the 2 Series Gran Coup\u00e9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a29476413/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-photos-info/|title=2020 BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe Is BMW's Odd Idea of an Economy Sedan|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Capparella|first=Joey|date=15 October 2019|accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe F44 2 Series was revealed online on 16 October 2019, and officially premiered at the [[Los Angeles Auto Show#2019|2019 Los Angeles Auto Show]] in November.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carscoops.com/2019/10/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-teased-one-last-time-ahead-of-tomorrows-debut/|title=2020 BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe Teased Ahead Of Tomorrow's Debut|date=2019-10-14|website=Carscoops|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> It was launched in worldwide markets in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/bmw-outs-new-2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-16595741/|title=BMW outs new 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|date=2019-10-16|website=SlashGear|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Development and launch ==\nThe 2 Series uses the [[front-wheel drive]] based [[BMW UKL platform|UKL architecture]] and uses a [[multi-link suspension|multi-link]] rear suspension system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbuyer.com.sg/2-series-gran-coupe-bmw-2019-new-singapore-reveal-mercedes-benz-cla/|title=BMW's challenger to the Mercedes-Benz CLA arrives in Singapore Q1 2020|date=2019-10-16|website=CarBuyer Singapore|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> Compared to the [[BMW 2 Series (F22)|F22 2 Series]] Coup\u00e9, the F44 has {{convert|33|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} more knee room, {{convert|14|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} more headroom, and a {{convert|40|litres|cuft|abbr=}} larger [[trunk (car)|boot]] capacity at {{convert|430|litres|cuft|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/bmw/2-series/101129/new-2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-aims-to-topple-mercedes-cla|title=New 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe aims to topple Mercedes CLA|website=Auto Express|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nAll petrol and diesel engines are installed with particulate filters and meet the [[European emission standards|Euro 6d-TEMP emissions standard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drivetribe.com/p/world-premiere-bmw-2-series-gran-RS4ZgzwORxCiLzklAxLsSQ|title=World Premiere: BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|last=Nica|first=Gabriel|date=2019-10-16|website=DriveTribe|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> Diesel engines also have [[diesel exhaust fluid|AdBlue]] [[selective catalytic reduction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsbeezer.com/slovakiaeng/photo-new-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-the-smallest-four-door-coupe/|title=PHOTO: New BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe \u2013 the smallest four-door coupe|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n218i models are available with a 6-speed [[manual transmission]] or a 7-speed [[dual-clutch transmission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netcarshow.com/bmw/2020-2-series_gran_coupe/|title=BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe (2020)|website=NetCarShow.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> 228i xDrive, M235i xDrive, and 220d models are only available with an 8-speed [[automatic transmission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/auto/1773459/bmw-expands-2-series-lineup-with-gran-coupe|title=BMW expands 2 Series lineup with Gran Coupe|last=Limited|first=Bangkok Post Public Company|date=|website=www.bangkokpost.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Equipment ==\nStandard equipment includes full LED lights and 40:20:40 split folding rear seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carsguide.com.au/car-news/bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-2020-revealed-new-small-sedan-to-take-on-merc-a-class-and-audi-a3|title=BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe 2020 revealed: New small sedan to take on Merc A-Class and Audi A3|website=CarsGuide|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> [[Collision detection]] with braking intervention is also standard in European models.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carsome.my/news/item/this-is-the-first-ever-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-is-here|title=This is the first-ever BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|date=2019-10-16|website=Carsome Malaysia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> In addition to the basic model, the 2 Series is available in the Luxury and Sport line which adds 17-inch wheels and a sports steering wheel, and the M Sport line which adds 18-inch wheels, an M Sport steering wheel, and M Sport exterior styling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carwow.co.uk/news/4340/bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-revealed|title=BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe revealed {{!}} carwow|website=www.carwow.co.uk|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nOptional equipment includes ambient lighting, a [[sunroof|panoramic sunroof]], a 9.2-inch windshield reflected [[automotive head-up display|head up display]], and [[CarPlay|Apple CarPlay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cars.com/articles/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-poised-to-take-on-mercedes-cla-411280/|title=2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe Poised to Take on Mercedes CLA|last=|first=|date=|website=cars.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The F44 2 Series can be unlocked via [[near-field communication]] by holding a [[smartphone]] near the door handle, and can start the engine by placing the smartphone in the [[inductive charging|wireless charging]] tray.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://automacha.com/bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-details-and-pictures-shared/|title=BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe has just been unveiled|date=2019-10-16|website=Automacha|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The digital key can also be shared with up to 5 other smartphones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://motioncars.inquirer.net/63027/bmw-reveals-all-new-2-series-gran-coupe|title=BMW reveals all-new 2 Series Gran Coupe|website=motioncars.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe 2 Series is also available with [[iDrive]] 7 which features [[over-the-air programming|over-the-air software updates]] and a [[virtual assistant|digital assistant]] that can be activated by saying \"Hello BMW\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-features-specs-options/|title=2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe makes its case as the ultimate entry-level luxury sedan|last=Szymkowski|first=Sean|website=Roadshow|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The digital assistant learns the habits of the user over time and can control in-car functions, check the maintenance status, or answer questions about the vehicle's functions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carkeys.co.uk/news/5-cool-pieces-of-tech-on-the-new-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe|title=5 cool pieces of tech on the new BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|website=Car Keys|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe 2 Series uses the [[automobile navigation system|navigation system]] and camera data to prevent unnecessary gear changes when travelling through corners and to determine appropriate shutdowns for the [[start-stop system|engine start-stop system]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guideautoweb.com/en/articles/52803/|title=All-new 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe is Revealed|website=The Car Guide|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Models ==\n[[File:BMW F44 IMG 2569.jpg|thumb|Rear view]]\n=== Petrol engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Model\n!Years\n!Engine\n!Power\n!Torque\n!0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62 mph)\n|-\n|218i\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2019\u2013\n|[[BMW B38|B38B15]] <br> 1.5 L [[straight-three engine|I3]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|103|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 4,600\u20136,500 rpm\n|{{convert|220|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,480\u20134,200 rpm\n|8.7 s\n|-\n|228i xDrive\n|[[BMW B48|B46A20]] <br> 2.0 L [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|170|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,000 rpm\n|{{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,450\u20134,500 rpm\n|6.0 s\n|-\n|M235i xDrive\n|[[BMW B48|B48B20]] <br> 2.0 L [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|225|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,250 rpm\n|{{convert|450|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,750\u20134,500 rpm\n|4.9 s\n|}\n\n=== Diesel engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Model\n!Years\n!Engine\n!Power\n!Torque\n!0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62 mph)\n|-\n|220d\n|2019\u2013\n|[[BMW B47|B47D20]] <br> 2.0 L [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|140|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 4,000 rpm\n|{{convert|400|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,750\u20132,500 rpm\n|7.5 s\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.bmw.com/en/bmw-models/2-series-gran-coupe.html Official site]\n\n{{BMW cars: 2000s to 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:BMW model codes|F44]]\n[[Category:BMW vehicles|2 Series]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2019]]\n[[Category:Compact cars]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = BMW 2 Series Gran Coup\u00e9 (F44)\n| image        = 2020 BMW 2-Series 218i Gran Coup\u00e9 M Sport.jpg\n| caption      = 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe F44\n| manufacturer = [[BMW]]\n| aka          = \n| production   = November 2019\u2013present\n| assembly     = Germany: [[Leipzig]] ([[BMW Central Building|BMW Group Plant Leipzig]])\n| class        = [[Compact executive car|Subcompact executive car]]\n| body_style   = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| layout       = {{ubl\n  | [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel drive]]\n  | [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, all-wheel drive]] ([[xDrive]])\n  }}\n| platform     = [[BMW UKL platform]]\n| related      = [[BMW 1 Series (F40)]]\n| engine       = {{ubl\n  | 1.5 L [[BMW B38|''B38'']] [[straight-three engine|I3]]-[[turbocharger|T]] (petrol)\n  | 2.0 L [[BMW B47|''B47'']] [[inline-four engine|I4]]-[[turbocharger|T]] (diesel)\n  | 2.0 L [[BMW B48|''B46'' / ''B48'']] [[inline-four engine|I4]]-[[turbocharger|T]] (petrol)\n  }}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n  | 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n  | 8-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  | 7-speed [[dual-clutch transmission|DCT]]\n  }}\n| propulsion   = \n| wheelbase    = {{convert|2670|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|4526|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width        = {{convert|1800|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height       = {{convert|1420|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight       = {{convert|1350|-|1570|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| sp           = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''F44 BMW 2 Series''' is a [[subcompact car|subcompact executive car]] produced by [[BMW]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmwblog.com/2019/10/15/world-premiere-the-first-ever-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe/|title=WORLD PREMIERE: The first Ever BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|date=2019-10-15|website=BMW BLOG|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> It is also known as the 2 Series Gran Coup\u00e9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a29476413/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-photos-info/|title=2020 BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe Is BMW's Odd Idea of an Economy Sedan|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Capparella|first=Joey|date=15 October 2019|accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe F44 2 Series was revealed online on 16 October 2019, and officially premiered at the [[Los Angeles Auto Show#2019|2019 Los Angeles Auto Show]] in November.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carscoops.com/2019/10/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-teased-one-last-time-ahead-of-tomorrows-debut/|title=2020 BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe Teased Ahead Of Tomorrow's Debut|date=2019-10-14|website=Carscoops|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> It was launched in worldwide markets in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/bmw-outs-new-2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-16595741/|title=BMW outs new 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|date=2019-10-16|website=SlashGear|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Development and launch ==\nThe 2 Series uses the [[front-wheel drive]] based [[BMW UKL platform|UKL architecture]] and uses a [[multi-link suspension|multi-link]] rear suspension system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbuyer.com.sg/2-series-gran-coupe-bmw-2019-new-singapore-reveal-mercedes-benz-cla/|title=BMW's challenger to the Mercedes-Benz CLA arrives in Singapore Q1 2020|date=2019-10-16|website=CarBuyer Singapore|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> Compared to the [[BMW 2 Series (F22)|F22 2 Series]] Coup\u00e9, the F44 has {{convert|33|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} more knee room, {{convert|14|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} more headroom, and a {{convert|40|litres|cuft|abbr=}} larger [[trunk (car)|boot]] capacity at {{convert|430|litres|cuft|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/bmw/2-series/101129/new-2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-aims-to-topple-mercedes-cla|title=New 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe aims to topple Mercedes CLA|website=Auto Express|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nAll petrol and diesel engines are installed with particulate filters and meet the [[European emission standards|Euro 6d-TEMP emissions standard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drivetribe.com/p/world-premiere-bmw-2-series-gran-RS4ZgzwORxCiLzklAxLsSQ|title=World Premiere: BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|last=Nica|first=Gabriel|date=2019-10-16|website=DriveTribe|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> Diesel engines also have [[diesel exhaust fluid|AdBlue]] [[selective catalytic reduction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsbeezer.com/slovakiaeng/photo-new-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-the-smallest-four-door-coupe/|title=PHOTO: New BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe \u2013 the smallest four-door coupe|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n218i models are available with a 6-speed [[manual transmission]] or a 7-speed [[dual-clutch transmission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netcarshow.com/bmw/2020-2-series_gran_coupe/|title=BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe (2020)|website=NetCarShow.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> 228i xDrive, M235i xDrive, and 220d models are only available with an 8-speed [[automatic transmission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/auto/1773459/bmw-expands-2-series-lineup-with-gran-coupe|title=BMW expands 2 Series lineup with Gran Coupe|last=Limited|first=Bangkok Post Public Company|date=|website=www.bangkokpost.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Equipment ==\nStandard equipment includes full LED lights and 40:20:40 split folding rear seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carsguide.com.au/car-news/bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-2020-revealed-new-small-sedan-to-take-on-merc-a-class-and-audi-a3|title=BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe 2020 revealed: New small sedan to take on Merc A-Class and Audi A3|website=CarsGuide|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> [[Collision detection]] with braking intervention is also standard in European models.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carsome.my/news/item/this-is-the-first-ever-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-is-here|title=This is the first-ever BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|date=2019-10-16|website=Carsome Malaysia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> In addition to the basic model, the 2 Series is available in the Luxury and Sport line which adds 17-inch wheels and a sports steering wheel, and the M Sport line which adds 18-inch wheels, an M Sport steering wheel, and M Sport exterior styling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carwow.co.uk/news/4340/bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-revealed|title=BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe revealed {{!}} carwow|website=www.carwow.co.uk|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nOptional equipment includes ambient lighting, a [[sunroof|panoramic sunroof]], a 9.2-inch windshield reflected [[automotive head-up display|head up display]], and [[CarPlay|Apple CarPlay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cars.com/articles/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-poised-to-take-on-mercedes-cla-411280/|title=2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe Poised to Take on Mercedes CLA|last=|first=|date=|website=cars.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The F44 2 Series can be unlocked via [[near-field communication]] by holding a [[smartphone]] near the door handle, and can start the engine by placing the smartphone in the [[inductive charging|wireless charging]] tray.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://automacha.com/bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-details-and-pictures-shared/|title=BMW 2-Series Gran Coupe has just been unveiled|date=2019-10-16|website=Automacha|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The digital key can also be shared with up to 5 other smartphones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://motioncars.inquirer.net/63027/bmw-reveals-all-new-2-series-gran-coupe|title=BMW reveals all-new 2 Series Gran Coupe|website=motioncars.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe 2 Series is also available with [[iDrive]] 7 which features [[over-the-air programming|over-the-air software updates]] and a [[virtual assistant|digital assistant]] that can be activated by saying \"Hello BMW\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/2020-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe-features-specs-options/|title=2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe makes its case as the ultimate entry-level luxury sedan|last=Szymkowski|first=Sean|website=Roadshow|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The digital assistant learns the habits of the user over time and can control in-car functions, check the maintenance status, or answer questions about the vehicle's functions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carkeys.co.uk/news/5-cool-pieces-of-tech-on-the-new-bmw-2-series-gran-coupe|title=5 cool pieces of tech on the new BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe|website=Car Keys|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe 2 Series uses the [[automobile navigation system|navigation system]] and camera data to prevent unnecessary gear changes when travelling through corners and to determine appropriate shutdowns for the [[start-stop system|engine start-stop system]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guideautoweb.com/en/articles/52803/|title=All-new 2020 BMW 2 Series Gran Coupe is Revealed|website=The Car Guide|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Models ==\n[[File:BMW F44 IMG 2569.jpg|thumb|Rear view]]\n=== Petrol engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Model\n!Years\n!Engine\n!Power\n!Torque\n!0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62 mph)\n|-\n|218i\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2019\u2013\n|[[BMW B38|B38B15]] <br> 1.5 L [[straight-three engine|I3]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|103|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 4,600\u20136,500 rpm\n|{{convert|220|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,480\u20134,200 rpm\n|8.7 s\n|-\n|228i xDrive\n|[[BMW B48|B46A20]] <br> 2.0 L [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|170|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,000 rpm\n|{{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,450\u20134,500 rpm\n|6.0 s\n|-\n|M235i xDrive\n|[[BMW B48|B48B20]] <br> 2.0 L [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|225|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,250 rpm\n|{{convert|450|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,750\u20134,500 rpm\n|4.9 s\n|}\n\n=== Diesel engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Model\n!Years\n!Engine\n!Power\n!Torque\n!0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62 mph)\n|-\n|220d\n|2019\u2013\n|[[BMW B47|B47D20]] <br> 2.0 L [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]]\n|{{convert|140|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 4,000 rpm\n|{{convert|400|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,750\u20132,500 rpm\n|7.5 s\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.bmw.com/en/bmw-models/2-series-gran-coupe.html Official site]\n\n{{BMW cars: 2000s to 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:BMW model codes|F44]]\n[[Category:BMW vehicles|2 Series]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2019]]\n[[Category:Compact cars]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BMW_2_Series_(F44)"}
{"title_page": "James and Browne", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:James And Browne 1902 Boanerges on London to Brighton VCR 1992.jpg|thumb|The surviving 1902 model.]]\n[[File:James and Browne car.png|thumb|James and Browne car]]\n[[File:James and Browne gearbox.png|thumb|Horizontal section of James and Browne engine and gearbox, viewed from above.]]\n'''James & Browne''' was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[automobile]] manufacturer, based in [[Hammersmith, London]] between 1898 and 1910.\n\nThe James & Browne factory was located at the [[Chiswick]] end of King's Street in West London, and there was a car showroom on [[Oxford Street]].\n\nThe early cars had an unusual engine layout with the flywheel between the cylinders. The engines were mid-mounted in the chassis, and the cylinders were horizontal.  Drive was to the rear wheels via a 4-speed gearbox and chain. The gearbox is in 2 parts, linked by a connecting rod, the left one containing 2nd and 4th gear, and the right 1st, 3rd and reverse.\n\nThe 2-cylinder engine is rated at 9 HP, and is just over 2.5 liters in size. A [[total-loss oiling system]] is used on the car, lubricating 6 main oil-ways. James & Browne also launched a 4-cylinder version (16 HP), of a similar design to the horizontal 2-cylinder engine.\n\nIn 1906 a vertical-engined car was introduced known as the Vertex and available as either a 20&nbsp;hp four or 30/40&nbsp;hp six-cylinder.\n\n== Surviving cars ==\nOnly two of their cars are known to have survived, one built in 1902 and the other in 1904. T.B. Browne, one of the company's founders, remained interested in the condition of the two surviving cars throughout his life and still regularly met with the owners until the early 1960s.\n\n===1902 model===\nThe car was built in 1902 and transported by train from the James and Browne works in [[Hammersmith, London]] to Albrighton Station, [[Shropshire]]. The first owner was Mr. Norman McLean of The Blue House, [[Tong, Shropshire]]. Mr Mclean had the car painted in the colours of his stables which were yellow with black lining. The car was then moved to [[Tong Castle]], the home of his fianc\u00e9e, Miss Hartley. The Hartley family had leased [[Tong Castle]] from Lord Bradford since 1855. Miss Hartley\u2019s brother was [[John Hartley (tennis)]], the winner of the Wimbledon Gentlemen\u2019s Singles Championship in 1879 and 1880.\n\nMr. McLean decided that some alterations to the car were required and instructed Mr. Ernest Roy Spencer to carry out the work. The Spencers were blacksmiths and ran their business at 15 Broadway, [[Shifnal]],<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Watts |editor-first=Sylvia |title=Shifnal, A Pictorial History |year=1989 |publisher= |isbn=0-85033-686-4}}</ref> around three miles from [[Tong Castle]]. \n\nIn 1910 Mr. McLean decided to sell the car to Ernest Spencer for a nominal sum of \u00a320. The car was moved to Ernest Spencer\u2019s business premises. Mr. Spencer decided that Mr. Mclean\u2019s colour scheme was too conspicuous for general use and drinking trips, so decided to paint the car battleship grey with black piping. Mr. Spencer intended to convert the car to a pick-up truck for his business and fitted it with magneto ignition and a windscreen. However, with the outbreak of [[World War 1]] in Summer 1914, the car was mothballed and stored in a shed at the back of the premises and stayed there until 1929. \n\nIn 1929 it was decided to enter the car in the Old Crocks' Run to Brighton. The less permanent alterations to the car were removed and it was returned to as near original condition as possible. The car was entered in the Old Crocks' Run to Brighton on Sunday 20th October (entry number 25) and departed from the Mall at around 9am. The ambitious cargo for the journey to Brighton consisted of five passengers, their luggage and a quantity of beer. The car had a good run but lost time when the battery terminals shook loose, and was the fifth car to arrive in Brighton.\n\nIn December 1929 ownership of the car passed to Mr. Herbert Ford who purchased the car from the Spencers for the sum of \u00a335. Mr. Ford was a local man and shrewd businessman, and had owned nearby [[Lilleshall Hall]] since 1927. In 1930, Mr. Ford opened some pleasure gardens for the public at [[Lilleshall Hall]], and these included an amusement park, narrow gauge railway and children's playgrounds. The car was used as an attraction in the amusement park. Mr. Ford and his friend, Mr. T.R. Price, entered the car in the 1933 Old Crocks' Run on Sunday 12th November 1933. The car (entry number 21) completed the run successfully with an average speed of 19.61 mph. \n\nIn October 1934 the car was purchased by John Garland, Dick and Edward Riddle, three students at the City and Guilds College, part of [[Imperial College London]]. The car has been an active part of college life from 1934 to the present day. The car is still maintained by students and is driven in many events including the [[London to Brighton Veteran Car Run]].\n\n===1904 model===\nThe first owner of the 1904 car was The Reverend Dr. John Darlington, the vicar of St Mark's Church, [[Kennington]] in London, who also owned a house in [[Curry Rivel]], near [[Taunton]] in Somerset. The Reverend had originally owned a Peugeot which had badly let him down in 1905, and as a friend of his had a reliable two-cylinder James & Browne car he visited the Showroom in Oxford Street and asked to buy a car \"like the one my friend owns\".  Browne remembered this visit as he had to advise Darlington that the Company had ceased making two-cylinder models in 1904, but he could offer Darlington a new four-cylinder 1905 model. Darlington was adamant that he wanted a two-cylinder car, so it was arranged that an unused two-cylinder engine, gearbox and transmission from the workshop be fitted into a compatible spare chassis, but with a later model body designed for the four-cylinder car.\n\nErnest Proctor, who was employed at the Westcroft Works, was given the job of assembling this hybrid car, which comprised a very early two-cylinder engine - number 30 - of 1901 or 1902 vintage, a 1904 chassis - number 126, and a body destined for four-cylinder car number 156.\n\nTechnical data:\n:Engine: No.30. Twin-cylinder horizontal, each cylinder 4\" dia. x 6\" stroke. Inlet valves suction operated: exhaust valves mechanically operated. Water-cooled, with no pump or cooling fan.\n:Ignition: 6 volt battery producing ignition via 2 trembler coils (originally also fitted with magneto with switching between trembler and magneto as required). Conventional spark plugs.\n:Lubrication: Drip feed from reservoir on dashboard via sight glasses to 6 oiling points on main bearings and pistons.\n:Gearboxes: Two boxes - one for 1st. 3rd. and reverse, the other for 2nd. and 4th. with a sliding shaft between the two. Lubrication by splash feed in each box.\n:Transmission: Main drive from engine to gear boxes via heavy steel spur gear into a mating 'Buffoline' rawhide gear attached to the flywheel on the crank shaft.\n:Final Drive: By two chains via a differential.\n:Brakes: Foot brake operates on transmission. Hand brake is a conventional drum brake on the rear wheels only.\n:Wheels/tires: Originally wooden wheels with solid tires, but these were changed in the early years to Sankey type metal wheels and fitted with balloon tires.\n:Lighting: Side and rear lamps - oil (paraffin). Headlamps acetylene - gas produced from carbide/water accumulator.\n\nThe car was first registered Y184 and was delivered to Darlington at Kennington Vicarage on 10 March 1906. It was used in London until it was driven to Curry Rivel on 23 April 1906 by Henry Lucas, a James & Browne salesman, who remained with the owner for some time after delivery, to teach him how to drive and maintain the vehicle.\n\nThe car was driven by Darlington, accompanied by his eldest son John, in 1913/1914, on a 2,000 mile tour of Europe. At the outbreak of World War 1, the car was taken back to Kennington where it remained until about 1925, when John Darlington Jr. \"got it going again\", and drove it back to Curry Rivel. By this time Dr. Darlington had purchased an Armstrong, so the James & Browne was stored in a barn. \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nWhen the James & Browne Company ceased trading, Henry Lucas (the salesman and chauffeur) with his colleague and friend Ernest Proctor were both made redundant. Lucas, with a partner John Drake, started a motor business in Egham, Surrey called the Egham Motor Company, and in 1914 asked Proctor to join them as Works Manager.\n\nWhile on holiday in Somerset in 1938, Lucas called at the house in Curry Rivel to see what had happened to the Darlington family; Dr. Darlington was still there and so was the James & Browne car..... in the barn. Dr. Darlington gave the car to Lucas who brought it back to Egham where he and Proctor restored it. It was then kept in the showroom of The Egham Motor Company for many years.\n\nHowever, when applying to register the car after its restoration, it was discovered that Dr. Darlington had transferred the original registration number, Y184, to his Armstrong, which was (and we believe, still is) on the road! \nSomerset County Council allocated the nearest unused number to the James & Browne ...Y182 - hence the temporary 2 was fixed over the 4 on the original number plates.\n\nAfter World War II the car was officially dated by the [[Veteran Car Club of Great Britain|Veteran Car Club]] as a 1904 model, and Lucas and Proctor entered it in the [[London to Brighton Veteran Car Run|London to Brighton Run]] in November 1948 - the first London to Brighton run for the car. Henry Lucas was driving and Ernest Proctor was passenger.\n\nProctor's eldest son, Sidney, joined his father and Henry on many of the early runs, until Ernest died in 1958.\nBy 1963, Lucas had become too infirm to continue to look after the car and, as he had no children, he sold the car to Sidney Proctor. On Sidney\u2019s death the car passed to his son. The car was in the Proctor family until it was auctioned in November 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bonhams: 1904 James & Browne 9hp Twin Cylinder Rear Entrance Tonneau 126|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/15346/lot/305/}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Stand 81, [[Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders|SMM&T]] 5th International Motor Exhibition February 1906==\n[[File:James & Browne car advertisement circa late 1906.png|thumb]]\nJames & Browne's display from the official catalogue:<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433112039171&view=1up&seq=9 The Society of Motor Manufacturers & Traders]</ref>\n:16-HP 4-cylinder ''J & B'' chassis: 4 speeds, 1 reverse, fitted with patent motor starter. Price \u00a3235 with tyres\n:16-HP 4-cylinder ''J & B'' double landaulette to seat four inside and two out. Price \u00a3385\n:30-HP 6-cylinder ''Vertex'' standard phaeton to seat five persons. Price \u00a3450\n:45-HP 6-cylinder ''Vertex'' saloon to seat seven persons. Price \u00a3775\n:45-HP 6-cylinder motor only on stand including set of parts manufactured by James & Browne Limited\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of car manufacturers of the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Veteran vehicles]]\n[[Category:Defunct motor vehicle manufacturers of England]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacture in London]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:James And Browne 1902 Boanerges on London to Brighton VCR 1992.jpg|thumb|The surviving 1902 model.]]\n[[File:James and Browne car.png|thumb|James and Browne car]]\n[[File:James and Browne gearbox.png|thumb|Horizontal section of James and Browne engine and gearbox, viewed from above.]]\n'''James & Browne''' was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[automobile]] manufacturer, based in [[Hammersmith, London]] between 1898 and 1910.\n\nThe James & Browne factory was located at the [[Chiswick]] end of King's Street in West London, and there was a car showroom on [[Oxford Street]].\n\nThe early cars had an unusual engine layout with the flywheel between the cylinders. The engines were mid-mounted in the chassis, and the cylinders were horizontal.  Drive was to the rear wheels via a 4-speed gearbox and chain. The gearbox is in 2 parts, linked by a connecting rod, the left one containing 2nd and 4th gear, and the right 1st, 3rd and reverse.\n\nThe 2-cylinder engine is rated at 9 HP, and is just over 2.5 liters in size. A [[total-loss oiling system]] is used on the car, lubricating 6 main oil-ways. James & Browne also launched a 4-cylinder version (16 HP), of a similar design to the horizontal 2-cylinder engine.\n\nIn 1906 a vertical-engined car was introduced known as the Vertex and available as either a 20&nbsp;hp four or 30/40&nbsp;hp six-cylinder.\n\n== Surviving cars ==\nOnly two of their cars are known to have survived, one built in 1902 and the other in 1904. T.B. Browne, one of the company's founders, remained interested in the condition of the two surviving cars throughout his life and still regularly met with the owners until the early 1960s.\n\n===1902 model===\nThe car was built in 1902 and transported by train from the James and Browne works in [[Hammersmith, London]] to Albrighton Station, [[Shropshire]]. The first owner was Mr. Norman McLean of The Blue House, [[Tong, Shropshire]]. Mr Mclean had the car painted in the colours of his stables which were yellow with black lining. The car was then moved to [[Tong Castle]], the home of fianc\u00e9e, Miss Hartley. The Hartley family had leased [[Tong Castle]] from Lord Bradford since 1855. Miss Hartley\u2019s brother was [[John Hartley (tennis)]], the winner of the Wimbledon Gentlemen\u2019s Singles Championship in 1879 and 1880.\n\nMr. McLean decided that some alterations to the car were required and instructed Mr. Ernest Roy Spencer to carry out the work. The Spencers were blacksmiths and ran their business at 15 Broadway, [[Shifnal]],<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Watts |editor-first=Sylvia |title=Shifnal, A Pictorial History |year=1989 |publisher= |isbn=0-85033-686-4}}</ref> around three miles from [[Tong Castle]]. \n\nIn 1910 Mr. McLean decided to sell the car to Ernest Spencer for a nominal sum of \u00a320. The car was moved to Ernest Spencer\u2019s business premises. Mr. Spencer decided that Mr. Mclean\u2019s colour scheme was too conspicuous for general use and drinking trips, so decided to paint the car battleship grey with black piping. Mr. Spencer intended to convert the car to a pick-up truck for his business and fitted it with magneto ignition and a windscreen. However, with the outbreak of [[World War 1]] in Summer 1914, the car was mothballed and stored in a shed at the back of the premises and stayed there until 1929. \n\nIn 1929 it was decided to enter the car in the Old Crocks' Run to Brighton. The less permanent alterations to the car were removed and it was returned to as near original condition as possible. The car was entered in the Old Crocks' Run to Brighton on Sunday 20th October (entry number 25) and departed from the Mall at around 9am. The ambitious cargo for the journey to Brighton consisted of five passengers, their luggage and a quantity of beer. The car had a good run but lost time when the battery terminals shook loose, and was the fifth car to arrive in Brighton.\n\nIn December 1929 ownership of the car passed to Mr. Herbert Ford who purchased the car from the Spencers for the sum of \u00a335. Mr. Ford was a local man and shrewd businessman, and had owned nearby [[Lilleshall Hall]] since 1927. In 1930, Mr. Ford opened some pleasure gardens for the public at [[Lilleshall Hall]], and these included an amusement park, narrow gauge railway and children's playgrounds. The car was used as an attraction in the amusement park. Mr. Ford and his friend, Mr. T.R. Price, entered the car in the 1933 Old Crocks' Run on Sunday 12th November 1933. The car (entry number 21) completed the run successfully with an average speed of 19.61 mph. \n\nIn October 1934 the car was purchased by John Garland, Dick and Edward Riddle, three students at the City and Guilds College, part of [[Imperial College London]]. The car has been an active part of college life from 1934 to the present day. The car is still maintained by students and is driven in many events including the [[London to Brighton Veteran Car Run]].\n\n===1904 model===\nThe first owner of the 1904 car was The Reverend Dr. John Darlington, the vicar of St Mark's Church, [[Kennington]] in London, who also owned a house in [[Curry Rivel]], near [[Taunton]] in Somerset. The Reverend had originally owned a Peugeot which had badly let him down in 1905, and as a friend of his had a reliable two-cylinder James & Browne car he visited the Showroom in Oxford Street and asked to buy a car \"like the one my friend owns\".  Browne remembered this visit as he had to advise Darlington that the Company had ceased making two-cylinder models in 1904, but he could offer Darlington a new four-cylinder 1905 model. Darlington was adamant that he wanted a two-cylinder car, so it was arranged that an unused two-cylinder engine, gearbox and transmission from the workshop be fitted into a compatible spare chassis, but with a later model body designed for the four-cylinder car.\n\nErnest Proctor, who was employed at the Westcroft Works, was given the job of assembling this hybrid car, which comprised a very early two-cylinder engine - number 30 - of 1901 or 1902 vintage, a 1904 chassis - number 126, and a body destined for four-cylinder car number 156.\n\nTechnical data:\n:Engine: No.30. Twin-cylinder horizontal, each cylinder 4\" dia. x 6\" stroke. Inlet valves suction operated: exhaust valves mechanically operated. Water-cooled, with no pump or cooling fan.\n:Ignition: 6 volt battery producing ignition via 2 trembler coils (originally also fitted with magneto with switching between trembler and magneto as required). Conventional spark plugs.\n:Lubrication: Drip feed from reservoir on dashboard via sight glasses to 6 oiling points on main bearings and pistons.\n:Gearboxes: Two boxes - one for 1st. 3rd. and reverse, the other for 2nd. and 4th. with a sliding shaft between the two. Lubrication by splash feed in each box.\n:Transmission: Main drive from engine to gear boxes via heavy steel spur gear into a mating 'Buffoline' rawhide gear attached to the flywheel on the crank shaft.\n:Final Drive: By two chains via a differential.\n:Brakes: Foot brake operates on transmission. Hand brake is a conventional drum brake on the rear wheels only.\n:Wheels/tires: Originally wooden wheels with solid tires, but these were changed in the early years to Sankey type metal wheels and fitted with balloon tires.\n:Lighting: Side and rear lamps - oil (paraffin). Headlamps acetylene - gas produced from carbide/water accumulator.\n\nThe car was first registered Y184 and was delivered to Darlington at Kennington Vicarage on 10 March 1906. It was used in London until it was driven to Curry Rivel on 23 April 1906 by Henry Lucas, a James & Browne salesman, who remained with the owner for some time after delivery, to teach him how to drive and maintain the vehicle.\n\nThe car was driven by Darlington, accompanied by his eldest son John, in 1913/1914, on a 2,000 mile tour of Europe. At the outbreak of World War 1, the car was taken back to Kennington where it remained until about 1925, when John Darlington Jr. \"got it going again\", and drove it back to Curry Rivel. By this time Dr. Darlington had purchased an Armstrong, so the James & Browne was stored in a barn. \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nWhen the James & Browne Company ceased trading, Henry Lucas (the salesman and chauffeur) with his colleague and friend Ernest Proctor were both made redundant. Lucas, with a partner John Drake, started a motor business in Egham, Surrey called the Egham Motor Company, and in 1914 asked Proctor to join them as Works Manager.\n\nWhile on holiday in Somerset in 1938, Lucas called at the house in Curry Rivel to see what had happened to the Darlington family; Dr. Darlington was still there and so was the James & Browne car..... in the barn. Dr. Darlington gave the car to Lucas who brought it back to Egham where he and Proctor restored it. It was then kept in the showroom of The Egham Motor Company for many years.\n\nHowever, when applying to register the car after its restoration, it was discovered that Dr. Darlington had transferred the original registration number, Y184, to his Armstrong, which was (and we believe, still is) on the road! \nSomerset County Council allocated the nearest unused number to the James & Browne ...Y182 - hence the temporary 2 was fixed over the 4 on the original number plates.\n\nAfter World War II the car was officially dated by the [[Veteran Car Club of Great Britain|Veteran Car Club]] as a 1904 model, and Lucas and Proctor entered it in the [[London to Brighton Veteran Car Run|London to Brighton Run]] in November 1948 - the first London to Brighton run for the car. Henry Lucas was driving and Ernest Proctor was passenger.\n\nProctor's eldest son, Sidney, joined his father and Henry on many of the early runs, until Ernest died in 1958.\nBy 1963, Lucas had become too infirm to continue to look after the car and, as he had no children, he sold the car to Sidney Proctor. On Sidney\u2019s death the car passed to his son. The car was in the Proctor family until it was auctioned in November 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bonhams: 1904 James & Browne 9hp Twin Cylinder Rear Entrance Tonneau 126|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/15346/lot/305/}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Stand 81, [[Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders|SMM&T]] 5th International Motor Exhibition February 1906==\n[[File:James & Browne car advertisement circa late 1906.png|thumb]]\nJames & Browne's display from the official catalogue:<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433112039171&view=1up&seq=9 The Society of Motor Manufacturers & Traders]</ref>\n:16-HP 4-cylinder ''J & B'' chassis: 4 speeds, 1 reverse, fitted with patent motor starter. Price \u00a3235 with tyres\n:16-HP 4-cylinder ''J & B'' double landaulette to seat four inside and two out. Price \u00a3385\n:30-HP 6-cylinder ''Vertex'' standard phaeton to seat five persons. Price \u00a3450\n:45-HP 6-cylinder ''Vertex'' saloon to seat seven persons. Price \u00a3775\n:45-HP 6-cylinder motor only on stand including set of parts manufactured by James & Browne Limited\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of car manufacturers of the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Veteran vehicles]]\n[[Category:Defunct motor vehicle manufacturers of England]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacture in London]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in London]]\n", "name_user": "Tromp78", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correction of minor errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_and_Browne"}
{"title_page": "White House Correspondents' Association", "text_new": "{{For|the press corps generally|White House press corps}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = White House Correspondents' Association\n| image = White House Correspondents' Association logo.jpg\n| abbreviation = WHCA\n| formation = {{Start date and years ago|1914|02|25}}\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|38.897776|-77.055130|display=inline, title}}\n| tax_id = 52-0799067<ref name= irseos>\"[https://apps.irs.gov/app/eos/pub78Search.do?ein1=52-0799067&names=&city=&state=All...&country=US&deductibility=all&dispatchMethod=searchCharities&submitName=Search White House Correspondents Association]\". ''Exempt Organization Select Check''. [[Internal Revenue Service]]. Retrieved July 10, 2017.</ref>\n| status = [[501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization]]<ref name= irseos/>\n| employees = 0<ref name= 990-2015>\"[http://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2015/520/799/2015-520799067-0cb54d92-9.pdf Form 990: Return of Organization Exempt from Income Tax]\". ''White House Correspondents' Association''. [[Guidestar]]. October 31, 2015.</ref>\n| employees_year = 2015\n| revenue = $366,481<ref name= 990-2015/>\n| revenue_year = 2015\n| expenses = $311,090<ref name= 990-2015/>\n| expenses_year = 2015\n<!-- | mission = To promote excellence in journalism and educate the public about the field of journalism and the process of reporting about the White House.<ref name= 990-2015/> -->| leader_title = [[President (corporation)|President]]\n| leader_name = Jonathan Karl ([[ABC News]])<ref name= officers>\"[https://www.whca.press/about/officers/]\". ''White House Correspondents' Association''. Retrieved July 25, 2017.</ref>\n| leader_title2 = [[Executive Director]]\n| leader_name2 = Steven Thomma<ref name= officers/>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.whca.press/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''White House Correspondents' Association''' ('''WHCA''') is an organization of journalists who cover the [[White House]] and the [[President of the United States]].  The WHCA was founded on February 25, 1914 by journalists in response to an unfounded rumor that a [[United States congressional committee]] would select which journalists could attend press conferences of President [[Woodrow Wilson]].<ref name=\"WHCA History\">{{cite web | url=http://whca.press/history.htm | title=Unfounded Leak Leads to Modern WHCA by George Condon, former president of the WHCA | publisher=White House Correspondents' Association | accessdate=August 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe WHCA operates independently of the White House. Among the more notable issues handled by the WHCA are the credentialing process, access to the President and physical conditions in the White House press briefing rooms.<ref name=\"WHCA Officers\">{{cite web | url=http://whca.press/officers.htm | title=White House Correspondents' Association Officers and Board | publisher=WHCA | accessdate=August 20, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Compton\">[http://www.editorandpublisher.com/news/incoming-whca-prez-critics-will-not-affect-next-year-s-dinner/ Joe Strupp, \"Incoming WHCA Prez: Next Year's Dinner Will Not Be 'Politically Correct\", ''Editor and Publisher'', April 25, 2007]</ref> Its most high-profile activity is the annual [[#White House Correspondents' Dinner|White House Correspondents' Dinner]], which is traditionally attended by the President and covered by the news media.\n\nNot every member of the White House press corps is a member of the White House Correspondents' Association.\n\n== Association leadership, 2018\u20132019 ==\nThe current leadership team of the White House Correspondents' Association includes:<ref name=\"WHCA Officers\"/>\n* Officers\n** President: [[Jonathan Karl]], [[ABC News]]\n** Vice President: [[Zeke Miller]], [[Associated Press]]\n** Secretary: Todd Gillman, ''[[The Dallas Morning News|Dallas Morning News]]''\n** Treasurer: [[Doug Mills (photographer)|Doug Mills]], ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* Board members\n** [[Steven Portnoy]], [[CBS News Radio]]\n** [[Tamara Keith]], [[NPR]]\n** Fin Gomez, [[CBS News]]\n** Francesca Chambers, [[Daily Mail]]\n**Anita Kumar, [[Politico]]\n* Executive Director\n** Steven Thomma<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whca.press/|title=WELCOME TO THE WHITE HOUSE CORRESPONDENTS' ASSOCIATION WEB SITE|website=www.whca.press|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== Table of association presidents ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" | Employer\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1914|1920}} || [[William Wallace Price]]  || ''[[The Washington Star]]''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1921|1922}} || Frank R. Lamb || ''The Washington Star''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1922|1923}} || J. Russell Young || ''The Washington Star''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1923|1924}} || E. Ross Bartley || [[Associated Press]]\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1924|1925}} || Isaac Gregg || ''[[The Sun (New York)|The Sun]]''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1925|1926}} || George E. Durno || [[International News Service]]\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1926|1927}} || John Edwin Nevin || ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1927|1928}} || John T. Lambert || [[Universal Service (news agency)|Universal Service]]\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1928|1929}} || J. Russell Young || ''The Washington Star''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1929|1930}} || Wilbur Forrest || ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1930|1931}} || Lewis Wood || ''[[The New York Times]]''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1931|1933}} || Paul R. Mallon || syndicated columnist\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1933|1934}} || George E. Durno || International News Service\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1934|1935}} || Francis M. Stephenson || Associated Press\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1935|1936}} || Albert J. Warner ||''New York Herald Tribune''\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1936|1937}} || Frederick J. Storm || [[United Press International|United Press Associations]]\n|-\n| {{Dash year|1937|1938}} || Walter J. Trohan || ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|-\n| {{Das